  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2039353160" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2039353160" />
    <a title="Maximilian W." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68881688-maximilian-w"><img alt="Maximilian W." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498349846p2/68881688.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2039353160?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maximilian W." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maximilian W." href="/user/show/68881688-maximilian-w">Maximilian W.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2039353160" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6452391635384152821">Allow me to preface this short review by explaining that I am not a fan of Donald Trump. In fact, quite the contrary: I believe him to be an idiotic buffoon with no idea of what he is doing or the responsibility he has somehow managed to undertake. That does not make me a supporter of Hillary Clinton or even, as America narrowly defines it, a &apos;liberal&apos;. As such, I have tried to read this book with as much of a free and open mind as possible, untainted by support of Trump or his policies *or* the</span>
  <span id="freeText6452391635384152821" style="display:none">Allow me to preface this short review by explaining that I am not a fan of Donald Trump. In fact, quite the contrary: I believe him to be an idiotic buffoon with no idea of what he is doing or the responsibility he has somehow managed to undertake. That does not make me a supporter of Hillary Clinton or even, as America narrowly defines it, a 'liberal'. As such, I have tried to read this book with as much of a free and open mind as possible, untainted by support of Trump or his policies *or* the same for Mrs. Clinton in the recent election.<br /><br />That being said: This book is one of the most unethical, diatribetic, and downright disingenuous works of propaganda possible. I have to compliment Snyder, however. He manages to obscure meaning and create dichotomy in the way that only a student of fascism would be able.<br /><br />The entire book reads like a long, sprawling manifesto, devoid of any truth or justice in its shameless pursuit of political agenda. I knew I was reading a well-made work of propaganda by page four, whereupon Synder claims that "Both fascism and communism were responses to globalization; to the real and perceived inadequacies it created[...]." While this is true, although a simplification, in the case of fascism, it is an outright lie in the case of communism, and one that underlines Snyder's entire justification of the ideology - and, for that matter, 'tyranny' in general. Communism was not a rejection of globalization, nor has it ever been. It was the *embracement* of a globalized world, spawned from Marx and Engel's explicit attempt to create a unified human society under a singular, just government. In fact, the word 'internationalist', which characterized the USSR and would later come to be redefined as 'globalist', has its origins in the seeples of communism. But this matters nothing to Snyder. No, because it is convenient for the present moment, Communism becomes a reactionary movement, a perversion of the flawless style of liberal democracy. The idea that a progressive movement could become tyrannical and oppressive, or that authority may not be synonymous with oppression, counteracts Snyder's entire line that Trump represents an American trend towards tyranny, which is birthed from purely reactionary motions such as his. Out the window it goes.<br /><br />The whole of this manifesto proceeds to be a mixture of propaganda piece and 'survival guide', with Snyder snipping and cutting away words and their meanings in classical fascist style, rewriting history and personality at a whim. I don't particularly care to go through and collect all the examples of the shameless altercations that would leave Huxley and Orwell turning in their graves; spend ten minutes reading this book without a mindless dedication to Trump or Clinton and you'll see it well enough for yourself. Don't believe me? Just look at what's been pinned as a quote from this book, right on this Goodreads page, whereupon Snyder defines Trump as a nationalist (which he is) - and proceeds to shamelessly redefine what nationalism and patriotism mean, interpreting them in a bizarre and illogical way that would only make sense were one attempting to redefine nationalism as 'Extreme, warmongering, and singleminded patriotism'. For the record, it is not. A nationalist, Mr. Snyder, is a patriot who believes that individual nations hold the right to their sovereignty, and - simultaneously - that the interests of each individual nation ought to be prioritized by said nation. It is not, as Snyder twists definitions around to mean, the idea that 'the only truth is the resentment we feel when we contemplate others'. The word you are looking for is Jingoism, which Mr. Trump is *not* a supporter of. But that, I'm sure, matters little to you, since nationalism sounds more effective when used as a propaganda piece. It is downright shameful that you would think to quote Orwell as a pawn in the game of obscuring and redefining language to suit political ends.<br /><br />Mr. Synder, in short, is either a shortsighted idiot who cannot understand that he is using the game of oppression to combat it, or, far more likely, a malicious scholar of Fukuyama who believes that the only way to attack 'fascism' is to practice it. <br /><br />Anyway, if you needed any hard evidence that the Ivy League has degenerated and is nothing more than a name for the same kinds of political machines present throughout all of America, here it is!</span>
  <a data-text-id="6452391635384152821" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

