<div id="review_3066053703" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3066053703" />
    <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus"><img alt="Settare (on hiatus)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590610257p2/13198822.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3066053703?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Settare (on hiatus)" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus">Settare (on hiatus)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Everyone!</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=azta-club">azta-club</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=social-issues">social-issues</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=politics-philosophy">politics-philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=to-re-read">to-re-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=war-conflict">war-conflict</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=on-tyrants-and-dictators">on-tyrants-and-dictators</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3066053703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18266296701576538161">I read this in the right place at the right time. <br/><br/>This was originally a series of Facebook posts that Snyder published every night for 21 nights right before the American 2016 presidential election. It consists of short, conscience, and neatly written lessons on what makes a fascist (or tyrant or dictator), how fascists come to power, and how tyranny is still a threat in modern times to all of us. He makes examples from Nazi Germany (his area of expertise) to make his arguments more understandab</span>
  <span id="freeText18266296701576538161" style="display:none">I read this in the right place at the right time. <br /><br />This was originally a series of Facebook posts that Snyder published every night for 21 nights right before the American 2016 presidential election. It consists of short, conscience, and neatly written lessons on what makes a fascist (or tyrant or dictator), how fascists come to power, and how tyranny is still a threat in modern times to all of us. He makes examples from Nazi Germany (his area of expertise) to make his arguments more understandable. <br /><br />Snyder's words are powerful, clear, short, and to the point. I would recommend this book to everyone and anyone, even though I might not have personally agreed with his every single opinion.<br /><br />The only thing that put me off is that he is clearly and exclusively addressing an American audience. This book is written <i>for</i> Americans and if you're reading it as a non-American, you have to make sense of a few things that are specific to the American society. For example, he insists way too much on the importance of being <i>"patriotic"</i> and what it means to be patriot. That's a word I dislike, but I understand that <i>patriotism</i> has certain connotations within the American society that might not have the same meaning elsewhere. <br />Still, patterns of tyranny are so similar around the world that those of us reading it outside America can make easy comparisons and draw multiple lessons from the book and it's just as important. <br /><br />The only other problem is that the writing feels a bit rushed. It reads like a compelling and noteworthy blog post that you might read online during some turbulent political times; it is not, however, a 'timeless masterpiece'. He could have worked on the draft to bring more nuance and subtlty to the writing when he decided to publishit as a “book”. <br />But as a whole, I think it's an important and compelling read. <br /><br />I'd recommend it to everyone, because I think the author makes some points that are worth reading, contemplating, and talking about. <br />I would love to know everyone's opinions about this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18266296701576538161" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


